    <p>Figure <xref ref-type="fig" rid="F1">1</xref> illustrates two of the fusion genes identified by TopHat-Fusion. Figure <xref ref-type="fig" rid="F1">1a</xref> shows the reads spanning a fusion between the <italic>BCAS3 </italic>(breast carcinoma amplified sequence 3) gene on chromosome 17 (17q23) and the <italic>BCAS4 </italic>gene on chromosome 20 (20q13), originally found in the MCF7 cell line in 2002 [<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="B22">22</xref>]. As illustrated in the figure, many reads clearly span the boundary of the fusion between chromosomes 20 and 17, illustrating the single-base precision enabled by TopHat-Fusion. Figure <xref ref-type="fig" rid="F1">1b</xref> shows a novel intra-chromosomal fusion product with similarly strong alignment evidence that TopHat-Fusion found in BT474 cells. This fusion merges two genes that are 13 megabases apart on chromosome 17: <italic>TOB1 </italic>(transducer of ERBB2, ENSG00000141232) at approximately 48.9 Mb; and <italic>SYNRG </italic>(synergin gamma) at approximately 35.9 Mb.</p>
